04915nam a22006735i 9780824862404DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20042004hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248624047 a10.1515/97808248624042doi  a(DE-B1597)484390  a(OCoLC)875895218  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aBQ649.T32 -- C42 2004eb 7aPHI0280002bisacsh04a294.3/9261 aChandler, Stuart, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEstablishing a Pure Land on Earth :bThe Foguang Buddhist Perspective on Modernization and Globalization /cStuart Chandler. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (392 p.) :billus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTopics in Contemporary Buddhism ;v2600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tSeries Editor’s Preface -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 A Mountain Monastery in an Urban Society -- t2 Master Xingyun: Foguang Patriarch -- t3 Foguang Humanistic Buddhism -- t4 Humanistic Buddhism in Practice -- t5 Cultivating Talent through Education -- t6 Cultivating Faith through Discipline -- t7 Institutionalizing Buddhism -- t8 Perpetuating Traditional Modernism -- t9 Globalizing Chinese Culture, Localizing Buddhist Teachings -- t10 Globalizing and Localizing: Three Case Studies -- tConclusion: Global Homelessness -- tAppendix: Chronological Table: Master Xingyun and Foguangshan -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith more than 150 temples in thirty countries, Foguangshan has developed over the last thirty-five years into one of the world’s largest and most influential Chinese Buddhist movements. The result of two years of fieldwork in Foguangshan temples in Taiwan, the U.S., Australia, and South Africa, this volume is an unprecedented examination of the inner workings of a dynamic and innovative religious movement. Based on direct observations, private interviews, and careful textual and historical analysis, Stuart Chandler looks at the challenges faced by Foguangshan’s leader, Master Xingyun, and his followers as they try to adhere to traditional practices and values while tapping into the advantages afforded by modern, global society. Foguangshan’s slogans (“Humanistic Buddhism” and “Establishing a Pure Land on Earth”) are placed in historical context to reveal their role in shaping the group’s attitudes toward capitalism, women’s rights, and democracy, as well as toward the traditional Chinese virtue of filial piety and the Chinese Buddhist concept of “links of affinity” (jieyuan). Chandler goes on to analyze Foguangshan’s educational system and its understanding of how precepts relate to contemporary problems such as abortion and capital punishment. The book’s final chapters consider the cultural and political dynamics at play in Foguangshan’s ambitious attempt to spread Humanistic Buddhism around the world and how its followers have reinterpreted the Buddhist ideal of homelessness to take advantage of the spiritual potentialities of people’s lives as global citizens.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Buddhist.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486240440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824862404423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824862404.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066325-9  University of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015 